The effect is therefore as if he had said, ‘than to write such a savage verse as that in the Eighth Satire' Cf. 1, 4, 92, where a line of simi- lar character is quoted from 1, 2, 27. That quotation is intro- duced by ,ego si risi and the argu· ment, there seriously made, is that the line is a harmless jest.⁴ lt is almost a necessary inference that here also the verse quoted by Tre- batius was regarded by Horace as in fact quite harmless.
